<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="128" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="128">
Named by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" author="Zotov, VD" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="21" pageNumber="140" pagination="539 - 544" refId="B22" refString="Zotov, VD, 1971. Simplicia T.Kirk (Gramineae). New Zealand Journal of Botany 9: 539 - 544, DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" title="Simplicia T. Kirk (Gramineae)." url="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" volume="9" year="1971">Zotov (1971)</bibRefCitation>
for John Buchanan FLS (1819-1898), Scottish born draughtsman, and New 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Zealand’s">Zealand's</normalizedToken>
first government employed botanist (
<bibRefCitation author="Taylor, M" journalOrPublisher="Auckland Botanical Society Bulletin" pageId="21" pageNumber="140" refId="B19" refString="Taylor, M, 2002. Meanings and origins of Botanical Names of New Zealand Plants. Auckland Botanical Society Bulletin 26" title="Meanings and origins of Botanical Names of New Zealand Plants." volume="26" year="2002">Taylor 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Buchanan first described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zotov, New Zealand J. Bot. 9: 542" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Zotov" class="Insecta" family="Gramineae" genus="Simplicia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Simplicia buchananii" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buchananii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Simplicia buchananii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="128" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Poa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa uniflora" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="128" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uniflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Poa uniflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Buchanan but that species name was preoccupied (
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa uniflora" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="128" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uniflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Poa uniflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Muhl.) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" author="Zotov, VD" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="21" pageNumber="140" pagination="539 - 544" refId="B22" refString="Zotov, VD, 1971. Simplicia T.Kirk (Gramineae). New Zealand Journal of Botany 9: 539 - 544, DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" title="Simplicia T. Kirk (Gramineae)." url="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" volume="9" year="1971">Zotov 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="130" pageId="9" pageNumber="128" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="128">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="130" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Simplicia buchananii. A habitat, Kahurangi National Park, North West Nelson, South Island, New Zealand B growth habit and inflorescence C culm, leaf base, sheath and ligule D spikelet showing reduced glumes and lemma (images: J. R. Rolfe)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.75.10328.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/114295" pageId="9" pageNumber="128">5</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Plants gracile, tufted, 0.40-0.60(-1.0) m tall. Culms 0.40-0.80 m long, bright green when fresh, wiry, erect (sometimes with apices weakly pendant), culm internodes 3-5, elongated, glabrous; internodes 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
equal in length to subtending leaf-sheaths. Culm-nodes slightly swollen when fresh, glossy orange-brown to dark red-brown (0.1-)0.3-0.4(-0.5) mm long. Basal leaf-sheaths stramineous or dull brown, membranous, strongly ribbed, usually glabrous, sometimes scabrid on ribs or evenly, finely pubescent; hairs when present retrorse to patent, minute (0.06-0.08 mm long); mid stem and upper leaf-sheaths stramineous to green, membranous, strongly ribbed, glabrous. Ligule 2.0-3.5(-4.0) mm, membranous, lanceolate, apex erose to very deeply lacerate; glabrous. Leaf-blade 100-200 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(1.8-)3.0(-4.0) mm, green to yellow-green, flat, linear-lanceolate with acuminate apices, finely ribbed; adaxial ribs finely scabrid, abaxial ribs glabrous; margins smooth. Panicle (40-)160(-180) mm long, linear; rachis glabrous, branches (10-)30(-36) mm long, erect, glabrous (sometimes bearing minute antrorse prickle-teeth near pedicels), bearing spikelets almost to base, pedicels 0.6-1.0(-1.2) mm long, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
glabrous (sometimes bearing sparse, minute, antrorse prickle-teeth), 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
appressed to branchlets. Spikelets 2.8-3.0 mm, 1(-2)-flowered, lanceolate, light green to stramineous. Glumes green (
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
hyaline), glabrous, ovate-lanceolate to ovate, acute to subacute, 1-nerved, lower and upper glume margins entire, ciliate; lower glume 0.3-1.0 mm, upper glume 1.0(-1.6) mm. Lemma 2.6-3.0 mm, light green to grey, scabrid (densely covered in minute prickle-teeth), 3(-5)-nerved, 
<pageBreakToken pageId="10" pageNumber="129" start="start">ovate-lanceolate</pageBreakToken>
, acute to mucronate, sometimes with a minute subapical awnlet 0.06-0.08 mm long. Palea 2.4-2.8 mm, scabrid (densely covered in minute prickle-teeth), lanceolate, pale green to green, pubescent, 1-2-nerved. Rachilla prolongation 0.3-0.5 
<pageBreakToken pageId="11" pageNumber="130" start="start">mm</pageBreakToken>
, filiform, hyaline, glabrous. Stamens 3. Filaments 0.3 mm long, hyaline. Anthers 0.7-1.5 mm, purple or yellow. Ovary narrowly ovoid to weakly trigonous 1.0-1.25 mm long, green, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
glabrous (basal portion sometimes minutely ciliate); styles apical, 0.10-0.25 mm, hyaline; stigmas plumose, white. Caryopsis 1.3-1.5 mm long, laterally compressed, orange when mature. Chromosome number: 2 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="130">n</emphasis>
= 28 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" author="Zotov, VD" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="21" pageNumber="140" pagination="539 - 544" refId="B22" refString="Zotov, VD, 1971. Simplicia T.Kirk (Gramineae). New Zealand Journal of Botany 9: 539 - 544, DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" title="Simplicia T. Kirk (Gramineae)." url="http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1971.10430200" volume="9" year="1971">Zotov 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="986142" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.75.10328.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/114295" pageId="11" pageNumber="130" start="Figure 5" startId="F5">
